{"summary":"Amending soil with a mix of manure and inorganic fertilizers has been found to increase microbial biomass and activity in the soil [902]. Manure alone has also been shown to increase microbial biomass [902]. Additionally, the use of mixed manure and inorganic fertilizer amendments has been linked to increased soil organic carbon and reduced soil cracking [902]. In terms of crop yield, studies have shown an increase in maize Zea mays yield in soils amended with a mix of manure and inorganic fertilizers [902].

In a salt marsh environment, the addition of alginate as a soil amendment led to a greater density and height of smooth cordgrass Spartina alterniflora [3244]. However, the biomass of the cordgrass was similar to that in unamended plots [3244].

In a freshwater wetland, the addition of large amounts of compost to plots planted with tree seedlings resulted in a plant community characteristic of drier conditions and lower plant species richness and diversity three years later [3310]. However, the same study found that birch Betula saplings were larger in plots amended with large amounts of compost [3310]. Lower doses of compost had no significant effect on these outcomes [3310].","query":"What are the effects of amending soil with different types of organic materials?","action_ids":["902","3244","3310"]}

